  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Richard Davis Webb presumably wrote this letter to Caroline Weston. Richard D. Webb has been engrossed by two subjects: &quot;the recollection of my great domestic loss and the affairs of America.&quot; [The &quot;great domestic loss&quot; is a reference to the death of Richard Davis Webb&apos;s wife, Hannah Webb, who died on July 16, 1862.] He has just finished printing the second, enlarged edition of Professor John Elliott Cairnes&apos;s The Slave Power: It&apos;s Character, Career, &amp; Probable Designs: Being an Attempt to Explain the Real Issues Involved in the American Contest. Webb wishes that wealthy Americans, such as Caroline Weston&apos;s uncle (Joshua Bates?) and Mr. Peabody would endeavor to make the book better known. Richard D. Webb considers the it &quot;the ablest book on the subject ever written.&quot; He mentions De Witt&apos;s Jefferson and Democracy and the correspondence between Edwin Loring and Charles Loring. [The Correspondence on the Present Relations Between Great Britain and the United States, by Edwin W. Field and Charles Greely Loring was published in Boston, 1862.]</subfield>
